1
00:00:02,000 --> 00:00:04,000
[Music Playing] 

2
00:00:04,000 --> 00:00:16,859
One night, around 1 AM, in a small provincial city with no specified name, a young man about 27 years old or so enters a solitary wooden annex, visiting a construction engineer.

3
00:00:16,859 --> 00:00:29,600
Sitting on a sofa with a latticed back and hard leather cushions, he almost immediately notices a plate with an untouched boiled chicken on the window.

4
00:00:29,600 --> 00:00:35,059
My name is Armen Zakharian, and this is the literary channel Armen and Fyodor.

5
00:00:35,059 --> 00:00:48,200
Today, we are launching a new segment called "Episode." In it, we will closely examine a single fragment from the pages of world literature each time and analyze why this episode is special and how art works within it.

6
00:00:48,200 --> 00:00:59,899
For our first experiment, we have chosen one of the most eerie yet intriguing scenes from Fyodor Dostoevsky's novel "Demons."

7
00:00:59,899 --> 00:01:11,620
This episode is near the very end of the book, from its concluding part. Here, someone named Verkhovensky arrives at night at Kirillov's house and sees a boiled chicken with rice on the window.

8
00:01:11,620 --> 00:01:23,480
Although there is a loaded gun lying right next to the chicken, it is not the gun, but the chicken that plays the role of Chekhov's gun, ready to "go off."

9
00:01:23,480 --> 00:01:36,240
However, to understand the shot and its target, one must first figure out who these two are and how they ended up here, together in one room at night in the annex.

10
00:01:36,240 --> 00:01:45,840
Interestingly, Dostoevsky prepares the ground for this eerie nocturnal encounter already at the very beginning of the book, just as he introduces us to the characters.

11
00:01:45,840 --> 00:01:56,000
Kirillov is a young man of about 27. Verkhovensky mirrors him—also a young man of approximately 27 years.

12
00:01:56,000 --> 00:02:02,519
This deliberate similarity only underscores the deep differences between them.

13
00:02:02,519 --> 00:02:11,740
Kirillov is a vivid representative of Dostoevsky's famous lineup of fanatic heroes—characters too passionately absorbed by an idea, living and serving it.

14
00:02:11,740 --> 00:02:20,260
However, Kirillov has a different plan: he intends to die for an idea.

15
00:02:20,260 --> 00:02:35,480
Kirillov is obsessed with the notion of the "man-god." He approaches this idea through a question typical of 19th-century literature: how to live after renouncing God?

16
00:02:35,480 --> 00:02:37,080
Suppose God no longer exists.

17
00:02:37,080 --> 00:02:42,240
Suppose we no longer believe in Him, as Verkhovensky might put it, we've "decommissioned" Him.

18
00:02:42,240 --> 00:02:46,240
But the need to fill the void in His place remains.

19
00:02:46,240 --> 00:02:56,579
And while another Dostoevsky character in the same "Demons" remarks, "If there is no God, then what kind of captain am I?"

20
00:02:56,579 --> 00:03:02,860
Kirillov says, "If there is no God, then I can take His place."

21
00:03:02,860 --> 00:03:14,800
Remember, Grebenshchikov sang, "You feel a draft because this place is vacant." Kirillov senses that very draft and formulates a dreadful, insane thought, in which he himself then falls in love.

22
00:03:14,800 --> 00:03:36,880
If a man, he argues, decides to end his life not out of anger, fear, or malice, but merely because he has the right, he will transform all of humanity with this step and become a man-god.

23
00:03:36,900 --> 00:03:40,100
But there have already been millions of suicides, they tell him.

24
00:03:40,100 --> 00:03:47,440
"But not for this reason, all with fear and not for this," Kirillov replies.

25
00:03:47,440 --> 00:03:52,640
This insane approach of his bears an amazing resemblance to an episode from "Don Quixote."

26
00:03:52,640 --> 00:04:00,500
Remember when the bold hidalgo tells Sancho Panza that he plans to mimic the glorious knights of the past and go mad?

27
00:04:02,220 --> 00:04:07,420
The pragmatic Sancho then asks, "But do you have a reason to go mad, Señor? What is the reason?"

28
00:04:07,420 --> 00:04:25,760
"That's the point," Don Quixote replies, "the uniqueness of my endeavor is precisely in going mad without any reason."

29
00:04:25,760 --> 00:04:32,680
As we will soon observe, the echoes in the words of Kirillov and Quixote are not accidental.

30
00:04:32,920 --> 00:04:42,920
To implement his mad idea, Kirillov has a loaded revolver on the window next to the chicken.

31
00:04:42,580 --> 00:04:52,960
You might ask: then what is he waiting for, why doesn't he carry out his intention if he doesn't need a reason for it?

32
00:04:52,960 --> 00:04:59,360
This is where his nighttime visitor, the revolutionary and nihilist Pyotr Stepanovich Verkhovensky, comes into play.

33
00:04:59,360 --> 00:05:09,080
This character is entirely different—an extraordinary hero, both funny and terrifying, comical to the point of parody, talkative and theatrical.

34
00:05:09,080 --> 00:05:14,659
Yet terrifying because he is prepared for any evil.

35
00:05:14,659 --> 00:05:21,500
Verkhovensky resembles Mephistopheles in some ways, though Mephistopheles had a better sense of humor.

36
00:05:21,500 --> 00:05:25,500
And due to life experience and age, he was more modest.

37
00:05:25,500 --> 00:05:29,280
The main thing they share: Verkhovensky is an extremely practical person.

38
00:05:29,280 --> 00:05:44,100
He believes that the end justifies any means. Intervening with the intriguing project of ideological suicide, Verkhovensky immediately thinks of how it can serve his cause.

39
00:05:44,100 --> 00:05:51,680
Not for a rebirth of humanity, he doesn't believe in that at all, but for his diabolical business.

40
00:05:51,680 --> 00:06:00,540
He decides to commit a political murder, and since Kirillov doesn't care when or how to die, he asks him to write a confession for this murder before his death. 

41
00:06:00,540 --> 00:06:07,220
In other words, to use Kirillov's death as an alibi for his crime.

42
00:06:07,220 --> 00:06:18,180
Thus, at the moment of their nocturnal meeting, we have a conflict of the spiritual—and though sick, Don Quixote was also mad—and the material; 

43
00:06:18,180 --> 00:06:22,639
the conflict of the elevated and the grounding, the tragic and the pragmatic.

44
00:06:22,639 --> 00:06:26,239
But how to show this through a single image?

45
00:06:26,239 --> 00:06:34,799
With the help of a chicken. The episode, as is often the case with Dostoevsky, unfolds rapidly.

46
00:06:34,799 --> 00:06:45,520
Verkhovensky has just entered, has just clarified: "Our intentions remain valid? I hope we are not backing down from suicide, we will sign the paper?" and almost without 

47
00:06:45,520 --> 00:06:51,699
pause, suddenly, he notices something on the window, on the plate. 

48
00:06:51,699 --> 00:06:58,499
He approaches the window. Wow, a boiled chicken with rice, but why is it still untouched?

49
00:06:58,499 --> 00:07:04,620
"We're in such a state of mind that even the chicken..." -- "I ate!" Kirillov interrupts him.

50
00:07:04,620 --> 00:07:09,020
"It's none of your business, be silent!" -- "Of course, and besides, it's all the same to you now".

51
00:07:09,020 --> 00:07:22,080
"But to me, it's not the same, you see. Imagine, I've hardly had lunch, so if the chicken is now, I assume, not needed anymore..."

52
00:07:22,080 --> 00:07:26,080
Pay attention to how Kirillov formulates his response: "Eat, if you can."

53
00:07:26,000 --> 00:07:28,800
Verkhovensky can, oh he can, for himself and for that guy.

54
00:07:28,800 --> 00:07:43,060
"Thank you," he says, and then: "and some tea." And something even creepier follows, the worm in the cherry on the top of this scene.

55
00:07:43,060 --> 00:07:52,580
Verkhovensky readily settled at the table on the other end of the sofa and with extreme greed attacked the meal, yet watched his victim every moment.

56
00:07:52,580 --> 00:07:59,760
Kirillov looked at him with angry disgust, motionless, as if unable to tear himself away.

57
00:07:59,760 --> 00:08:07,480
Verkhovensky represents the triumph of the flesh here; he eats greedily, with appetite, with fervor.

58
00:08:07,480 --> 00:08:11,580
After all, the person sitting a meter from him is about to shoot himself, but the chicken is therefore up for grabs.

59
00:08:11,580 --> 00:08:25,100
Notice, in just this paragraph, Verkhovensky takes away everything from Kirillov: his freedom, his last will, his last meal, and finally, his life.

60
00:08:25,100 --> 00:08:35,959
The chicken is, of course, only a metaphor, because in essence, Verkhovensky is a cannibal; people to him are expendable material, feeding his petty ambitions and plans.

61
00:08:35,959 --> 00:08:42,400
Is the happiness of mankind worth a child's tear? — asks Ivan Karamazov.

62
00:08:42,400 --> 00:08:48,600
“A child with garnish or just plain?” Verkhovensky clarifies.

63
00:08:48,600 --> 00:09:04,020
And Kirillov, this strange Kirillov, yes with his insane idea, but still with an unmalicious heart, can't tear himself away, he watches in horror as Verkhovensky

64
00:09:04,020 --> 00:09:09,660
eats the chicken. Because he's eating not just it but also him, Kirillov, right now.

65
00:09:11,459 --> 00:09:22,680
"Verkhovensky-Barabek munched a man and didn’t look back. Forty more, then cow and bull, butcher bent and belly full; cart and hoop and broom and vice, poker, mop, and boiled rice. Chicken too — with rice precise — and then, he chewed up paradise."

66
00:09:22,680 --> 00:09:35,760
And all this tangle of contradictions, fears, and fates Dostoevsky shows through one dining scene, through one plate of cold chicken with rice.

67
00:09:35,080 --> 00:09:45,260
The eloquent horror of this gastronomic scene was very accurately captured in the legendary production of "Demons" by the St. Petersburg Maly Drama Theater in a six-hour 

68
00:09:46,500 --> 00:09:50,500
performance by Lev Dodin, which played on stage for almost 30 years.

69
00:09:50,500 --> 00:09:56,440
Those who were lucky enough to attend this performance surely remember the scene with Verkhovensky’s chicken.

70
00:09:56,440 --> 00:10:08,460
Having seen this once live, it’s hard to forget. So take a look at a fragment of how this scene was played.

71
00:10:27,440 --> 00:10:35,440
We could end the discussion of today's fragment here if it weren't for one detail. 

72
00:10:35,440 --> 00:10:47,320
that this juxtaposition of refusal from food—gluttony, as a metaphor for a value conflict, appeared in one book which

73
00:10:47,320 --> 00:10:54,320
Dostoevsky greatly cherished, a book that influenced all of his main texts, a book he said had no equal in the world in depth or strengh.

74
00:10:54,320 --> 00:11:06,320
Finally, the book that we mentioned today—of course, "Don Quixote" by Cervantes. 

75
00:11:06,320 --> 00:11:10,320
Remember how the relationship between Don Quixote and Sancho Panza is structured in the first volume. We spoke about this in one of the early episodes of "Armen and Fedor" dedicated to this novel.

76
00:11:10,320 --> 00:11:25,000
Sancho is fixated on food, he constantly reminds Quixote about it, and at every opportunity, he strives to eat, regardless of whether his master is sermonizing, fasting, or suffering. 

77
00:11:25,000 --> 00:11:35,320
And the great American director Orson Welles, in his "Don Quixote," which coincidentally will be released nearly simultaneously with Dodin's play,

78
00:11:35,320 --> 00:11:57,320
will depict a scene painfully reminiscent of this episode from "Demons." There, Sancho Panza will be greedily devouring, in the presence of a fasting Quixote, what do you think? Of course, a chicken.

79
00:11:57,320 --> 00:12:20,320
 

80
00:12:25,320 --> 00:12:35,960
It remains only to note that while this episode corresponds quite well to the spirit of Cervantes' Don Quixote, it does not fully match the text.

81
00:12:35,960 --> 00:12:38,360
In the novel's text, there was no such chicken scene.

82
00:12:38,360 --> 00:12:49,000
However, after all, it is easily explained: Cervantes did not read Dostoevsky, unlike Orson Welles.

83
00:12:49,040 --> 00:12:55,240
This is the literary channel of Armen and Fyodor, the "Episode" segment.

84
00:12:55,240 --> 00:13:06,480
I hope the experiment with this new concise format was successful, and if so, write to us in the comments what other episodes you would like to see in this segment in the future.

85
00:13:06,480 --> 00:13:11,080
Meanwhile, that's all. My name is Armen Zakharian. Until next time.

86
00:13:12,880 --> 00:13:28,360
[Music Playing]

